# where go fits in the c / rust / zig discussion


# the category problem

# c, rust, and zig are *systems languages* — they compete for kernel code,
# drivers, embedded, codecs, anything where you care about exact memory layout
# and not having a runtime. go is an applications language with systems-ish
# ambitions. it has a garbage collector, a goroutine scheduler, and a runtime
# that's always there. that puts it in a different bucket than the other three.


# what go is actually for (and dominating)

# - cloud infrastructure. docker, kubernetes, etcd, prometheus, grafana,
#   terraform, vault, consul, caddy, traefik, minio, nats, cockroachdb,
#   influxdb, tidb. the entire cncf landscape is mostly go.
# - backend services / apis. net/http + stdlib is enough for a huge chunk of
#   rest/grpc work. discord, uber, twitch, cloudflare, dropbox.
# - cli tools. github cli, hugo, fzf-style tools — anything that needs to ship
#   a single static binary that runs anywhere.
# - devops glue. *the* default language for ops tooling now — replaced python
#   in a lot of places where startup time and single-binary distribution
#   mattered.


# why go won this niche

# 1. compiles to a single static binary. no runtime to install, no shared
#    libs, no python virtualenv. scp it and run it. this alone won most of
#    cloud-native.
# 2. cross-compilation is trivial. GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build works out
#    of the box, no toolchains. (zig is even better here; go got there first
#    for a mainstream audience.)
# 3. concurrency that's actually usable. goroutines + channels are easier than
#    threads + locks. easier than rust's async ecosystem. easier than c's
#    "roll your own."
# 4. the language is small. read the spec in an afternoon. new hires are
#    productive in a week.
# 5. backed by google. stable, well-resourced, won't be abandoned. compare to
#    rust foundation drama or zig's pre-1.0 status.


# where go isn't in the c/rust/zig conversation

# - no kernel / driver / embedded work. the gc and runtime make go a
#   non-starter for code that runs below the os or with hard real-time
#   constraints. tinygo exists for microcontrollers but it's a niche fork.
# - no "manual memory" story. can't write a high-performance allocator in go,
#   can't avoid the gc, can't lay out cache-friendly structures the way
#   c/rust/zig let you.
# - performance ceiling. go is *fast enough* for almost everything but has a
#   real ceiling vs c/rust/zig for compute-heavy work. game engines, codecs,
#   parsers handling millions of events/sec — you usually end up writing the
#   hot path in c via cgo, or you switch languages.
# - cgo is painful. go's ffi is famously the worst of any modern language.
#   every cgo call crosses a stack boundary, isn't optimized, and screws with
#   the scheduler. "if you find yourself reaching for cgo, you've picked the
#   wrong language."


# where go competes with each

# vs c    — if you'd write a daemon, an http server, a cli tool in c: don't.
#           use go. faster to ship, gc isn't a problem in this space,
#           deployment story is better.
# vs rust — the real overlap. both compile to single binaries, both target
#           backend services and cloud infra. choose rust if you need maximum
#           performance, no gc pauses, or the type system's correctness
#           guarantees. choose go if you want to ship 3x faster and your team
#           isn't already rust-fluent.
# vs zig  — almost no overlap. zig wants kernels and game engines; go wants
#           kubernetes controllers. they're not fighting for the same code.


# the five-language landscape (2026)

#                  runtime    gc    where it lives
# c               no         no    kernels, embedded, libs
# zig             no         no    same niche as c, better ergonomics
# rust            minimal    no    same niche as c + secure userland + new infra
# go              yes        yes   cloud-native, apis, clis, devops
# python/js       big        yes   apps, scripts, data science


# the mental model

# - c / zig / rust fight over the bottom of the stack.
# - go owns the middle: networked services, infrastructure tools, clis,
#   anything you'd deploy to a server.
# - python / typescript own the top: apps, scripts, ml, data.
#
# rust is the only one that crosses from the bottom into the middle
# convincingly — and that's why the "rust vs go" debate is real but the
# "zig vs go" debate basically isn't. zig isn't trying to build your next
# backend; go isn't trying to write your next kernel driver.


# practical 2026 picks

# - cli tool? go if i/o-bound and you want shipping speed; rust if you want
#   maximum polish; zig if it's tiny and embedded-ish.
# - backend service? go is the default; rust if you need the perf or
#   correctness; nothing else competes seriously here.
# - kernel module, codec, allocator, embedded firmware? c, zig, or rust.
#   not go.
# - cloud control plane (operator, crd, sidecar, etc.)? go, full stop. the
#   ecosystem is built around it.


# the takeaway

# go isn't *in* the c/rust/zig discussion so much as it's the language those
# three keep pointing at and saying "yeah but go already owns that part."
